</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ucaptainmeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Captain Meth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/4/01 3:43:12 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.methart.com/t_meth2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Best Pens For Inking + Markers</span><hr size=1> Once again, the Koh-I-Noor Rapidographs.  I live by them.  But I'm one of the few people at the board that actually likes them.  A lot of people prefer the Sakura Pigma Micron pen thingees.  I don't like them because they run out of ink fast, and the colour is a dull grey as opposed to a nice rich black.  On the other hand, they don't have metal tips making them less likey to ruin the paper surface like the Rapidographs will, and they're cheap.  But if you use them enough, eventually you'll spend more on those than the Rapidographs.  I have a write up on them at my site under tutorials. <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
You can't give it.  You can't even buy it.  And you just don't get it.
<br>
<img src="http://www.methart.com/signature.jpg"></img>

<a href="http://www.methart.com"><img src="http://www.methart.com/button/methart-fire2.jpg" border="0"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ubartekine.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bartekine</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/4/01 3:57:52 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Best Pens For Inking + Markers</span><hr size=1> For beginners starting out, I would recommend Sakura. Though I haven't actually tryed them, the vast majority of the forum express good things about them.<br>
If you continue to a more professional level, and developed your own style then you might want to experiment what works for you and your style best, and try different things. Also a good pen to pick up is a tombo (ABT) brush pen.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usid5150.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sid5150</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/4/01 4:06:35 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.liquid2k.com/sid_5150/motofun2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Best Pens For Inking + Markers</span><hr size=1>   IMHO Pigma makes a GREAT brush pen with archival ink.  The Tombos are just a fittle too meaty for my tastes.  However, If you really have to get used to a brush pen to use it well.<br>
<br>
   My fav is My Rotring EF Art Pen.  The ink is BLACK and its writes SMOOTHLY.  Paper selection and the angle/orientation of the nib need to be considered, lest you'll get spatter.<br>
<br>
<br>
Hope this helps...<br>
<br>
